**Idea:**

In this method, we iterate through each character in every line. We build each word character by character by including only alphabetic characters. When we encounter a non-alphabetic character (such as punctuation or whitespace), we complete the current word (if any) and add it to a set to ensure uniqueness. Finally, we sort the set and output the words.


**Time Complexity:**

The algorithm runs in O(n)O(n)O(n) where nnn is the total number of characters across all lines.
**Advantage:**

This approach is straightforward and gives you explicit control over how each character is handled.
Below are the implementations:

`#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;set&gt;
#include &lt;string&gt;
#include &lt;cctype&gt;
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int N;
    cin &gt;&gt; N;
    cin.ignore(); // Clear newline after reading the integer
    set&lt;string&gt; words;

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; N; i++) {
        string line;
        getline(cin, line);
        string word;
        for (char c : line) {
            if (isalpha(c)) {
                word.push_back(tolower(c));
            } else {
                if (!word.empty()) {
                    words.insert(word);
                    word.clear();
                }
            }
        }
        if (!word.empty()) {
            words.insert(word);
        }
    }

    cout &lt;&lt; words.size() &lt;&lt; "\n";
    for (auto &amp;wd : words)
        cout &lt;&lt; wd &lt;&lt; "\n";

    return 0;
}
