`**Idea:**

Instead of checking every character in detail, we can preprocess each line by converting it to lowercase and replacing every non-alphabetic character with a space. After this replacement, we can split the line into words using built-in functions, thereby simplifying token extraction.


**Time Complexity:**

The preprocessing still runs in O(n)O(n)O(n) per line.
**Advantage:**

This method leverages built-in functionalities to reduce explicit character-by-character handling, making the code more concise.
Below are the implementations:

`#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;sstream&gt;
#include &lt;set&gt;
#include &lt;string&gt;
#include &lt;cctype&gt;
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int N;
    cin &gt;&gt; N;
    cin.ignore();
    set&lt;string&gt; words;

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; N; i++) {
        string line;
        getline(cin, line);
        // Replace non-alphabetic characters with space and convert to lowercase
        for (char &amp;c : line) {
            if (!isalpha(c))
                c = ' ';
            else
                c = tolower(c);
        }
        istringstream iss(line);
        string token;
        while (iss &gt;&gt; token) {
            words.insert(token);
        }
    }

    cout &lt;&lt; words.size() &lt;&lt; "\n";
    for (auto &amp;word : words)
        cout &lt;&lt; word &lt;&lt; "\n";

    return 0;
}
``# Approach 2: Preprocessing with Character Replacement and Splitting
N = int(input())
words = set()

for _ in range(N):
    line = input().strip()
    # Replace any non-alphabetic character with a space and convert to lowercase
    processed = ''.join(ch.lower() if ch.isalpha() else ' ' for ch in line)
    for token in processed.split():
        words.add(token)

sorted_words = sorted(words)
print(len(sorted_words))
for w in sorted_words:
    print(w)
`**Idea:**

A powerful and concise method is to use regular expressions to split the input string by non-alphabetic characters. Regular expressions can easily handle multiple consecutive punctuation marks or spaces in a single operation.


**Time Complexity:**

Although regex operations have overhead, the constraints of the problem allow this approach to be sufficiently efficient.
**Advantage:**

This method is very concise and makes the code highly readable by abstracting away the details of character inspection.
Below are the implementations:

`#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;set&gt;
#include &lt;string&gt;
#include &lt;regex&gt;
#include &lt;cctype&gt;
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int N;
    cin &gt;&gt; N;
    cin.ignore();
    set&lt;string&gt; words;
    regex delim("[^a-zA-Z]+");  // Split on one or more non-alphabet characters

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; N; i++) {
        string line;
        getline(cin, line);
        // Convert line to lowercase
        for (char &amp;c : line) {
            c = tolower(c);
        }
        // Use regex_token_iterator to split the line
        sregex_token_iterator it(line.begin(), line.end(), delim, -1);
        sregex_token_iterator reg_end;
        while (it != reg_end) {
            string token = *it;
            if (!token.empty())
                words.insert(token);
            ++it;
        }
    }

    cout &lt;&lt; words.size() &lt;&lt; "\n";
    for (auto &amp;word : words)
        cout &lt;&lt; word &lt;&lt; "\n";

    return 0;
}
